##White Manual and green manual: Changes in diagnostic criteria of new coronary pneumonia

Wechat, bingdianweekly

Features, China Youth Daily's in depth reporting brand. We believe that news has more than one day of life.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A pedestrian enjoys the sunshine with open arms on Hualou Street in Jianghan district, Wuhan, Hubei Province, on February 16,2010. China Youth Daily China Youth Net Trainee Reporter, Lu Chong / photo

By Yang Hai

Editor, Zhang Guo

On the last day of 2019, several medical experts were dispatched to Wuhan by the National Health Commission. Almost all of them experienced the Atypical pneumonia epidemic of 2003, and many of them were very impressive in that big event.

A new epidemic awaits them. Later in the day, the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission issued its first report on the outbreak of viral pneumonia: 27 cases of pneumonia were found in the area, linked to the south China seafood market.

The disease was initially referred to as a "viral pneumonia of unknown origin" until January 8, when it was identified as a COVID-19. People's understanding of it from the beginning of complete ignorance, there is a gradual deepening of the process.

On January 16, the National Health Commission released the first edition of the "national level" diagnosis and treatment program, setting down the criteria for diagnosis. Prior to this, Wuhan as a focus area, in accordance with the standards groped out in the early screening and treatment.

Green Handbook and white handbook

After the New Year holiday, the hospital held a meeting, which was attended by department heads, Liu Yue, director of the Emergency Department at a top-three hospital in Wuhan, told reporters. The head of the college verbally conveyed to them a "reporting standard" for "viral pneumonia of unknown origin. " .

He clearly remembered that the head of the academy was holding a "white-bound manual. ".

Liu Yue's colleague Jing Kun (not his real name) , director of the hospital's Department of Critical Care Medicine, also said he heard "reporting standards" on the same occasion.

Another three a hospital emergency department director Li Xia (not his real name) also confirmed to reporters that on January 3, the hospital held a similar meeting.

"The leadership of the academy requires that this reporting standard can only be communicated by face-to-face, telephone or wechat voice, " Li said.

The "reporting standard, " as the doctors call it, refers to the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission's "unexplained viral pneumonia standards. ". Case does not meet this "into the standard" , there is no need to report.

A person familiar with the matter provided reporters with this copy of the standards. It stipulates that patients "with a history of epidemiology and clinical manifestations" can be included.

The "epidemiological history" consists of four articles, one of which is sufficient for the patient:

1. Traders, employers and workers who have been trading in the south China seafood market since December 1,2019.

2. Persons who have worked at the south China Seafood Market for more than three hours in the two weeks prior to onset of illness since December 1,2019, in processing, selling, slaughtering, processing and handling.

3. Since December 1,2019, those who had a clear history of contact with poultry or wild animals in the south China seafood market in the two weeks prior to the onset of symptoms (touching or close viewing within 1 meter, etc.) .

4. Those who live, live, study, accompany, share the ward with those who meet the case definition, or those who do not take effective protective measures.

As for "clinical manifestations" , there are also four:

1. Fever ≥38 °C.

2. Imaging features of pneumonia.

3. The total white blood cell count was either normal or decreased, or the lymphocyte count was reduced.

4. After Standard Antibiotic Treatment for 3 days, there was no obvious improvement or progressive aggravation.

According to the inclusion criteria, viral pneumonia patients who can not be clearly diagnosed with other diseases need to satisfy four "clinical manifestations" and one of four "epidemiological histories" to be included. Once included, patients need to be tested for other viral pneumonia such as influenza, Adenovirus, Mycoplasma, chlamydia pneumonia, and bacterial pneumonia, "with a definitive diagnosis of other diseases, " and ruled out.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Unexplained pneumonia enters the criteria. Cartography Li Qiang

"after the outbreak, the national and Provincial Health Committees attached great importance to it and sent a working group and an expert group to Wuhan to guide the local response and handling of the epidemic, " said the second report of the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission on Jan. 3.

However, an expert panel member of the China Youth Daily, interviewed by a reporter from the China Youth Daily, said they had not formulated such standards.

"I was never involved in the formulation of the standards, and the National Health Commission was not aware of the existence of the standards at the beginning, " a member of the first group of experts told reporters. "The standards were added later in Wuhan. "

The expert said he later saw the white-bound manual, part of which was the entry criteria.

A member of the second group of experts provided journalists with a green-bound manual on viral pneumonia medical treatment of unknown causes, printed with the words "Wuhan Health Commission" . The manual includes viral pneumonia for unknown causes (trial) , requirements for viral pneumonia for unknown causes, and 9 documents related to pathogenic diagnosis specimen collection, case transfer, autopsy and so on.

The panellist said that the two manuals with different color covers had different criteria for identification.

The first group of experts told reporters that the Green Book, "viral pneumonia for unknown reasons (trial) , " was jointly developed by them and local experts in Hubei, "around January 3. ".

According to the protocol in the Green Book, the "Case Definition" item explains which patients can be identified as "viral pneumonia cases of unknown origin. ".

"definition" a total of four criteria, namely: fever, with the imaging features of pneumonia, early onset of normal or reduced white blood cell count, or lymphocyte count reduction, 3 days after standard antibacterial treatment, there was no significant improvement or progressive deterioration.

Pneumonia can be defined as "viral pneumonia of unknown cause" if the patient has all four criteria and can not be definitively diagnosed as having any other disease.

The Standard in the green book also mentions "exposure to the south China market in Wuhan or similar patient exposure history" , but does not take this standard as a necessary condition, but as a floating condition -- if the case meets this standard, you only need to meet the first three of these four criteria to qualify as a "viral pneumonia case of unknown origin. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Green Book, viral pneumonia for unknown causes (trial) . Illustration by Li Qiang

Wuhan Doctors Liu Yue, Jing Kun and Li Xia all told reporters that they had never seen a green leather manual. They all believe that the White Paper Manual "into the platoon standard" is too "harsh" , is not conducive to early detection, early diagnosis.

The reporter noticed that the only difference between the white manual and the green manual is the addition of the standard. On the manual version of the question, the reporter asked the Wuhan City Health Commission, did not answer.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Left: the Green Book Catalog

Right: Catalogue of White Paper Manuals, cartography Li Qiang

"By that standard, we can't report any of them. "

After a meeting at the hospital on January 3, Jing Kun's department of critical care medicine immediately opened up more than 10 isolation beds for patients with pneumonia of unknown cause. From the time the first patient checked in, he recalls, it took him less than three days to fill his bed.

Jing Kun's hospital has drawn up an in-hospital report of suspected cases of pneumonia of unknown origin and the process of diagnosis and treatment.

"their clinical manifestations are so unique that there is no doubt that this is the disease, " Jing Kun said firmly. He did not refer to the "standards for admission to the platoon, " but took the initiative to report all of the more than 10 cases to the medical service and the hospital.

None of the dozen patients, however, were defined as "viral pneumonia of unknown origin" -- not a single patient met the inclusion criteria.

"Many patients do not have a history of exposure to the south China seafood market, some have a fever of less than 38 °C, and some have not undergone standard antimicrobial treatment, " Jing said.

On the wall of the doctors'lounge in his department hangs a screen showing surveillance videos of the dozen or so patients.

Usually, doctors identify them by their numbers, because they're so much alike: Most people are in a coma, with a windpipe in their neck, some even have an ECMO, and lie in bed motionless.

Their similarities are also reflected in the CT images of the lungs, "white, all white. ".

"Even such a patient does not meet the 'standards for admission to the platoon. ' " Jing Kun raised his voice, then remained silent for a few seconds.

A number of hospitals in Wuhan have implemented the Standard Foshan. According to reports, the Youfu hospital near the south China seafood market found that medical staff and inpatients were infected in early January, but the patients did not meet the diagnostic criteria because they did not have a history of contact with the south China seafood market, didn't report it.

Most of the viral pneumonia patients in Jing Kun's department were transferred from the Outer Hospital, and some had been "wandering around for more than a week" after their illness.

His disregard for "standards" in reporting cases quickly reverberated with "harsh criticism" from a hospital leader who "said we reported too much" .

Later, when the hospital became eligible for nucleic acid testing, more than 60 percent of the patients he treated were positive for pneumonia -- a diagnosis of new pneumonia. He told reporters that many of the remaining negative patients were close to recovery, and that there was a false negative factor in the nucleic acid test, as the president of the Chinese Academy of Medical Sciences, Wang Chen, had also pointed out that the quality of the nucleic acid test reagent was unstable, caused a lot of false negatives.

"according to this standard, we can't report any of them, " Jing said.

Also puzzling was the opening of fever clinics on January 1st in two wards of the hospital. Later statistics showed that January 4 became an inflection point in the number of patients. That day fever patients up, there are 102, "many times the normal. ".

"Our fever clinic is too small and is already full, so we have to drain the fever patients to the emergency department, " Li said.

By January 15,261 feverish patients had flocked to the hospital emergency room in a single day. These many "no place to sit" fever patients, it is difficult to be reported to the Wuhan Department of Disease Control.

"It was so strict that none of them met [ the entry criteria ] , " Li told reporters. The doctor also raised questions about the standards to hospital officials, especially "why do they require patients to have a history of exposure to the south China Seafood Market? " But received no response.

"All our preparations are not enough, " Li said. "The infectious disease ward needs three zones and two passages, and the wards should be separated by a certain distance. We can not do that. "

No new cases were reported between January 11 and January 15, according to the Wuhan Municipal Health Commission.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Street of Baibu Pavilion Community in Wuhan, China, Feb. 18,2010. A banner in front of a row of lanterns reads, "those who do not submit to the closed management of the residential area shall be dealt with seriously and in accordance with the law. ". Zhao di, China Youth Daily, China Youth Daily

An analysis of the epidemiological characteristics of COVID-19 pneumonia, completed by the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention in February, reviewed all cases reported in mainland China as of Feb. 11. According to the date of onset, 104 people were infected and 15 died before December 31,2019.

At different times, doctors at different hospitals in Wuhan have noticed a sudden rise in patients with fever. Lu Xiaohong of Wuhan's Fifth Hospital told reporters that she had advised her hospital to open a fever clinic, and since January 6, the hospital has received many suspected cases.

The famous Wuhan Union Hospital had to convert an entire floor of the Infectious Diseases Department into a respiratory quarantine zone.

January 23, Wuhan identified the first batch of new fixed-point pneumonia hospital. Until now, many patients, who could not be defined as "viral pneumonia of unknown origin" or "COVID-19 pneumonia" , had gone to hospitals without proper isolation.

The second group of Experts, Peking University First Hospital, arrived in Wuhan on Jan. 8 and learned that the incidence of pneumonia in a local hospital in December 2019 was 17 percent higher than in the same period last year. He contracted a new coronavirus while working in Wuhan.

Before Liu Yue's emergency ward was requisitioned as a pneumonia patient isolation ward, they received no risk alert. "We were wearing normal surgical masks and doing regular respiratory protection, " he says.

"We knew there was pneumonia, but we didn't know we had it, " Liu Yue told reporters. "there had been no increase in official figures and there was no obvious human-to-human transmission. "while we do this in the emergency department, other departments that are further away from infectious diseases are even more careless. "

On January 20, a high level expert group led by Zhong Nanshan held its first press conference after visiting Wuhan, and confirmed that human to human transmission and infection among medical personnel had occurred in Wuhan. One of the neurosurgical patients infected 14 medical staff.

Liu Yue was one of the doctors infected with the virus. The only possible exposure, he recalls, was a pneumonia patient admitted to their ward on Jan. 6, when he was given no warning of the danger. Later, when his 16 hospital beds were once occupied by four families, it was clear to him that "the disease is passed from person to person. ".

"early detection, early diagnosis, early isolation and early treatment should be achieved, and experts and resources should be focused on the treatment, " the Wuhan Municipal Health Commission said in a Jan. 11 announcement

And the National Health Commission repeatedly mentioned early detection, early reporting, early isolation, early treatment, "four early" principle slightly different, here, "early diagnosis" instead of "early report.

The National Standards were updated several times as the epidemic progressed

Unlike the 2003 SARS outbreak, China has quickly isolated the virus, sequenced its genes and shared the sequences with the World Health Organization for a global research response. The move was praised by the World Health Organization. On January 8, the pathogen was tentatively identified as COVID-19.

On the same day, a second group of experts arrived in Wuhan and, as part of their work, revised the viral pneumonia for unknown causes. Two days later, the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention developed a diagnostic kit that could be used to detect the virus, as well as RT-PCR.

"What I saw was a green book, and there was a nucleic acid test, so we added a 'confirmed case' criterion, and nothing else changed, " a member of the panel told reporters.

Many days later, according to the expert, a doctor in Wuhan called him and admitted that he had not told the expert group the Truth and that he had contracted the virus.

The three Wuhan Doctors told reporters that the criteria for "confirmed cases" had indeed been added at the time, but on the basis of the White Book, not the Green Book.

"Most of the cases received treatment were exposed to the south China Seafood Market in Wuhan, and some of the cases showed the characteristics of family clustering, and most of these clustered cases had the history of exposure to the market, " the reporter found in "the case characteristics of this epidemic" , a report in "the viral pneumonia of unknown causes (Trial Implementation) 

"We knew at the time that there had been a small cluster of cases, but these people were all connected to the south China Seafood Market, " said the panel member, who said the panel had concluded that "limited human-to-human transmission" was possible, because of what they learned in Wuhan.

On January 16, the National Health Commission released the first edition of the diagnosis and treatment plan for pneumonia caused by COVID-19 infection. At this point, Wuhan's pilot program was suspended.

On this day, in Wuhan City Health Commission's notification, many days "no new cases, " added 4 cases.

The definition of "observed case" (later changed to "suspected case") in the first edition of the National Health Commission's plan, "Epidemiological History" is related to "Wuhan" rather than the South China seafood market. "Clinical Presentation" provides for "fever, " but there is no specific standard for body temperature.

Since then, national standards have been revised several times as the epidemic progresses. Zhang Xiaochun, deputy director of Medical Imaging Department of Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University, suggested that nucleic acid test could not rule out false negative, and suggested CT imaging as the diagnostic method. Later Standards Incorporated such comments.

Since February 12, the standard in Hubei Province has been further relaxed to include "clinically diagnosed cases" for the first time, adding 14,840 new cases a day, including 13,332 clinically diagnosed cases. Zeng Yixin, deputy director of the National Health Commission, said the increase in clinical cases was aimed at facilitating early diagnosis and treatment of patients, early isolation, standardized treatment, and improve the success rate of treatment. "because of the program, the number of cases has really increased, which really reflects the situation in Wuhan, " he said.

On February 19, the National Health and Human Services Commission released the sixth edition of the diagnostic and therapeutic protocol. In the latest version, Hubei Province and other provinces outside Hubei Province to remove the distinction, unified into "suspected cases" and "confirmed cases" of two categories.

According to a report by the National Health and Human Services Commission on the morning of February 20,615 new cases were confirmed in Wuhan and 13 in four other cities in Hubei during the whole day of February 19, however, because 10 cities and states of the confirmed cases of the original "clinical diagnosis cases" for nucleic acid testing, nucleic acid test results were negative from the confirmed cases of the reduction, a total of 279 cases revised reduction, so Hubei announced 349 new confirmed cases. It was the first time that the number of new cases in one day fell to three digits in Hubei Province. With the deepening of knowledge, the improvement of national standard, the goal of "receive all and cure all" was also approaching. Reporter Jiaxing Wang contributed to this report
